Rating: 3
After reading through many of the reviews and including a few (accidental) additions of my own, I found this to be a fantastic dish, wonderful for chilly nights. I followed the basic recipe with these changes: I used 10 large chicken thighs instead of 6 in an effort to achieve a stew more than a soup. Because of the extra chicken, I added another piece of bacon and browned in batches. I doubled the garlic and because I was low on dried oregano, I included a bit of thyme, Italian seasoning and a few red pepper flakes, all in all about a tablespoon and a half of dry spices. I added several rinds of Parmesan Regganio cheese because I had been saving them for use in a soup and never had the opportunity. I added more wine to the pot to cover the extra chicken, simmered the thighs for well over 50 minutes, transferred to a bowl, removed the skin, deboned in chunks (not shreds) and returned accumulated juices and meat back to pot. I drained but did not rinse beans, and when I went to cut some fresh basil from my herb garden only to discover that the first frost had indeed ended growing season, I defrosted four "cubes" of pesto that I had made this past summer, and let freeze in ice cube trays. I figured - fresh basil and other ingredients - couldn't hurt?! All ingredients in pot, I let simmer a bit more -- and was delighted to see that what had looked like a "chunky" soup started to indeed look like a stew - and it smelled terrific. This dish was superb with an arugla salad, crusty bread and a glass (or two) of Pinot Noir. Yum.

